 Key Points About JavaScript (JS):
 
 1. JavaScript was created in 1995 by Brendan Eich at Netscape to make web pages interactive.

2. Its original name was Mocha, then LiveScript, before finally being renamed to JavaScript.

3. JavaScript is a high-level, interpreted programming language that runs in the browser.

4. Microsoft created its own version called JScript for Internet Explorer in 1996.

5. ECMAScript (ES) is the standardized version of JavaScript, maintained by ECMA International.

6. ES1 was released in 1997, marking the official standardization of JavaScript.

7. ES3 (1999) introduced regular expressions, better string handling, and exception handling.

8. AJAX (2005) allowed web pages to load data asynchronously without reloading the page.

9. jQuery, released in 2006, simplified DOM manipulation and cross-browser coding.

10. Node.js, introduced in 2009, allowed JavaScript to run on the server side.

11. ES5 (2009) added strict mode, JSON support, and useful array methods like map() and filter().

12. ES6 (2015) brought major features such as let, const, arrow functions, classes, and modules.

13. Frameworks like React, Angular, and Vue.js made JavaScript ideal for building web apps.

14. TypeScript, a superset of JavaScript, added type safety and became popular for large projects.

15. JavaScript supports asynchronous programming using promises and async/await.

16. Modern runtimes like Deno and Bun aim to make JavaScript development faster and safer.

17. JavaScript can now run on mobile, desktop, and IoT devices besides browsers.

18. ES2022 introduced features like top-level await and private class fields.

19. JavaScript is the core of front-end development, powering interactive web experiences.

20. As of 2025, JavaScript remains one of the most widely used programming languages worldwide.